        June 7, 2009<br><br>All You Wonderful Sons and Daughters of God .. actually or potentially --<br><br>Today is the feast of the Holy Trinity .. and I'd like to honor the Trinity by sharing the following with you.<br><br>Very recently I heard a false statement regarding the Trinity. &quot;When Jesus suffered and died, the Father suffered and wept.&quot; If we are speaking anthropomorphically, okay, yes. But if we are speaking literally, exactly, NO, it is not possible for the Father to suffer and weep.<br><br>The Blessing of the Trinity be poured upon us all!<br>The following statements are totally true &gt;&gt;&gt;<br><br>Any form of suffering necessarily means change.<br><br>The Person of the Father cannot change, cannot suffer.<br><br>The Person of the Holy Spirit cannot change, cannot suffer.<br><br>The Person of the Son CONSIDERED AS IDENTICAL WITH THE DIVINE NATURE and <i>NOT</i> IN HIS HUMAN NATURE cannot change.<br><br>The human nature of Jesus Christ CAN change, can and did suffer and die and rose from the dead.<br><br>The Second Divine Person CAN SUFFER AND DIE <i>IN HIS HUMAN NATURE ONLY</i> .. and, understanding that .. it is proper to say that the Second Divine Person, GOD, Suffered and Died (in His human nature).<br><br>The truths stated above involve what is known as &quot;Communicatio Idiomatum,&quot; or &quot;the Communication of Idioms.&quot;<br><br>Blessed be the Most Holy Trinity .. and thanks be to God we have received God's Revelation! Blessing on us ALL!<br><br>What say you?<br>John (JohnJFarren) <a href="mailto:Trinity@aol.com">Trinity@aol.com</a>
