        June 20, 2009<br><br>JMJ / MMM     090620  Sunday<br>Hello Ned --<br>You wrote, “<font color="Blue">It is in that statement I AM that I station my faith. That may all sound very Buddhist, except that my experience has shown me that this I AM is a creative living Being and not a dead concept.It is loving because it begets all things. It is intelligent because all knowledge proceeds from it.</font>”<br><br>My first remark -- In my reading I’ve encountered some Buddhists, not Theravada but Mayahana, not many but a few, who seem to have “touched” God.  There’s a big thing about Buddhists and “no God.”  I am skeptical that Buddha did not recognize the existence of God.  He was often asked, “<font color="blue">Is there a God?” .. Does the soul exist after death?</font>”  And similar questions.  Buddha would never answer.  That did NOT mean he implied “no.”  Part of Buddha’s teaching was that each one must “be a light to himself,” that each one must find the truth in an experiential way.  He would say, “<font color="blue">Hey! don’t believe this or that because of ME.  No way!  You follow the 8-fold way that I’ve laid out and you will come to know the truth.</font>”<br><br>My second remark -- A short, true story -- I was spending a week as a guest with the Trappist monks in Massachusetts.  After we cleaned up after a good meal, a monk and I sat charring in the cleared refectory.  We shared a little about Buddhism.  I asked him, “<font color="blue">What is the rock difference between Christianity and Buddhism?</font>”  I looked forward to an involved discussion.  Without a moment’s hesitation he cut immediately to the heart of the whole thing, the monk instantly responded, “<font color="blue">Jesus Christ.</font>”  That was it.  At that time I was a little disappointed.  Several weeks later it suddenly occurred to me that was the best answer the monk could possibly have given.  Without Jesus Christ we are without the fullness of the choicest gifts God wants to give us.  With Jesus Christ only we have the very Fullness of God Himself -- as much as we are prepared or ready to receive it.<br>Every blessing, Ned.         John</span>
