        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: Ned</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 13, 2009<br><br>Hi John,<br><br>If you haven't read Pope Benedict's &quot;Introduction to Christianity&quot; I highly recommend it. That book has had a lot to do with my personal return to faith in Christ and the Church. <br><br>In that book, the Pope talks about Being as Truth or the Logos. Being is eternal and omnipresent and I would add intelligent and living. Becoming, on the other hand, is temporal and singular. Along with that idea and what you said above, I was reminded of an insight I had quite a while ago.<br><br>We spend most of our lives trying to define who we are: &quot;I am (fill in the blank)&quot; and we all use that statement &quot;I am...&quot; <br><br>Whatever we finish off that statement with is bound to change and it is different for each one of us. There was a time before we were born when it could not be applied to us (because we didn't exist yet). And there will be a time after we are dead when it also would not apply. Yet, I AM was there before we were born, is here now and will be there after we are gone. No matter how we define it or how many times we change the definition it remains unchanged.<br><br>It is in that statement I AM that I station my faith. That may all sound very Buddhist, except that my experience has shown me that this I AM is a creative living Being and not a dead concept.It is loving because it begets all things. It is intelligent because all knowledge proceeds from it. <br>This is exactly how the Trinity is described. From the <a href="http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/02033b.htm" target="_blank">Athanasian Creed</a>:<br><br>The Father is made of none, neither created, nor begotten. The Son is of the Father alone; not made, nor created, but begotten. The Holy Ghost is of the Father, and of the Son neither made, nor created, nor begotten, but proceeding.</span>
