        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: Rev. Brandon A. Olivares</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 9, 2009<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by NightSpirit</div><br><br>But would it be inaccurate to also assume from this verse that God actually can have arms, like a man? Taken with other verses, such as &quot;let us make man in our image&quot; and how in Genesis 18, the Lord appeared to Abraham in the form of a man, that would seem a fair conclusion.<br><br>Taking a verse literally like Psalm 91:4 - He shall cover thee with his feathers, and under his wings shalt thou trust - along with about 10 other verses in psalms, as well as Ruth 2:12, might lead one to believe God has feathers on His arms or wings instead of arms. Maybe He does or maybe not; whether we take it as stated or poetically, it really doesn't alter the intended truth in the verse, that He will protect us.</blockquote><br><br>This is a perfect example of how God discusses things according to our own experience in order to get a point across. Of course he really doesn't have arms, or wings for that matter, but it helps us to better understand what he is talking about. Again, the exact same thing Jesus did. Jesus is not actually a vine, obviously, but it helps us get a better picture of what he is talking about.<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by NightSpirit</div><br><br>In the one verse above, what would you think would be the beneficial effect of adding the word &quot;anger&quot; to that? If we assume that the underlying event that is describe in verse 20 will actually happen to those who do verse 19, why do you think that tone was created by those words?<br><br>Why would God, in whose image I am made, speak this way or allow himself to be characterized as angry and jealous if He is not really going to be angry with those, as in this instance, who know the truth and oppose it? <br><br>Jesus said in  Matthew 12, &quot;But I say unto you, That every idle word that men shall speak, they shall give account thereof in the day of judgment.&quot; Wouldn't God also choose His words as carefully, as Jesus asked of us? <br><br>If God is never angry, it seems it would have been more accurate and as simple to say, &quot;If you go against me to serve your own imagination, I will blot you out.&quot; I don't know. Please give me your thoughts.   <br><br>Is it figurative language also that the Holy Spirit can be &quot;grieved&quot; or that there will be a day for the &quot;wrath&quot; of God?</blockquote><br><br>Well, if someone's angry, aren't people going to be a lot more careful what they do? So much more if the one who is angry is God? People will say, &quot;we better do what he is saying.&quot;<br><br>I have a theory that every act of God, every merciful act and every punishment, comes directly out of his nature. It is what had to happen. From the beginning, he knew that Jesus would come to earth.</span>
