        June 9, 2009<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by JohnJFarren</div><br><br>It was necessary to tell a story -- or not be understood at all -- of a man and a woman in a Garden with special trees and with a serpent who would talk and introduce a temptation.  <br><br>It took many, many ages for that story to be properly understood.  <br><br>For very many people, is that story understood today?  In its important, essential elements, yes.  But many people -- the security of their faith depends upon it -- take the story literally, word true for word true.  Well, that’s another story..</blockquote><br><br>I can't really agree that the story was not understood immediately, as it was happening and before it was recorded, just as well as any of us understand it now. But like you said, that's another story or at least another thread. <br><br>I have been seeking God for more enlightenment on the original story and look forward to delving more into it here at a later time.<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by JohnJFarren</div><br><br>The key to the answer of the original question about God suffering essentially depends on the absolutely necessary truth that suffering involves change .. and on a (partial) understanding of the Incarnation.</blockquote><br><br>God can change His form as He did with Abraham or as He did with Moses, from a cloud by day and a fire by night. He can change his decisions as He did with Hezekiah. He can change His methods and symbols from animal sacrifices to the Lamb of God, from circumcision of the flesh to the circumcision of the heart. He can limit Himself, as in promising not to flood the earth again. He can change His own laws of physics and science when we pray.<br><br>Would He have to change His entire nature to feel empathy and compassion at the Crucifixion?  I'm not saying He was worried or wringing His hands, that He lost sight of the purpose of the cross, just that, at that moment, He may have cared and allowed Himself to be there and share the experience, instead of being disinterested or unaffected.<br><br>I'm willing to admit I may be missing something, especially considering the thought you've put into the question so thanks for your patience. <br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by JohnJFarren</div><br><br>Blessing to all!         John</blockquote><br><br>Double blessings in one post! Thanks again. It's a blessing just reading what you write. Thanks.</span>
