        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: NightSpirit</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 9, 2009<br><br><blockquote>Deuteronomy 29: 19 And it come to pass, when he heareth the words of this curse, that he bless himself in his heart, saying, I shall have peace, though I walk in the imagination of mine heart, to add drunkenness to thirst: 20 The LORD will not spare him, but then the anger of the LORD and his jealousy shall smoke against that man, and all the curses that are written in this book shall lie upon him, and the LORD shall blot out his name from under heaven.</blockquote><br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by JohnJFarren</div><br><br>However, they are powerful and special ways of saying something.  The word “anthro” refers to man, to human beings.  There are times when Scripture speaks of God in terms of man, as if God were a human.being.  (We are not considering Jesus, True God and a true man, here.)  This is not a way of descendingly talking to dumb, little children.  It’s a manner of human speaking (under the inspiration of God) that is meant to add effect.</blockquote><br><br>In the one verse above, what would you think would be the beneficial effect of adding the word &quot;anger&quot; to that? If we assume that the underlying event that is describe in verse 20 will actually happen to those who do verse 19, why do you think that tone was created by those words?<br><br>Why would God, in whose image I am made, speak this way or allow himself to be characterized as angry and jealous if He is not really going to be angry with those, as in this instance, who know the truth and oppose it? <br><br>Jesus said in  Matthew 12, &quot;But I say unto you, That every idle word that men shall speak, they shall give account thereof in the day of judgment.&quot; Wouldn't God also choose His words as carefully, as Jesus asked of us? <br><br>If God is never angry, it seems it would have been more accurate and as simple to say, &quot;If you go against me to serve your own imagination, I will blot you out.&quot; I don't know. Please give me your thoughts.   <br><br>Is it figurative language also that the Holy Spirit can be &quot;grieved&quot; or that there will be a day for the &quot;wrath&quot; of God? <br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by JohnJFarren</div><br><br>There is a time for “talking down” to people.  How should God have described the creation and formation of the world to the ancient Jews?  By explaining the Big Bang?  By explaining the relationship of matter to energy?  Or by using the words (which didn’t exist then and nor did their concepts) “prior” and “subsequent”?  No.</blockquote><br><br>We are so much in agreement here about it being unneccesary for God to go into a full explanation of everything. But I think his reasons for doing so are far greater than the limits of that society or the current scientific knowledge. <br><br>I believe God has revealed the truth in the Bible in encapsulated form and then reveals Himself, His truths, His secrets further to those who seek Him out.</span>
