        June 9, 2009<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by JohnJFarren</div><br><br>JMJ / MMM     090608<br>A Blessing on You, NightSpirit .. and Everybody --</blockquote><br><br>Thanks, and to you too. <br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by JohnJFarren</div><br><br>What’s about “not literal”?  Examples= Oh, don’t beat around the bush!  There ain’t no bush.  And I’m not beating anything.  //  I’m gonna knock your block off!  You’d be arrested for nurder .. better not do it.  //  Said about somebody’s boss &gt; Boy! that guys a bear!  In actual fact, he’s not.  //  And .. she can wrap him around her little finger.  But you see the point.  In each of these statements there is meaning -- clearly understood.  You grasp the truth of them.  But taking each word at its face value .. they’re gibberish.</blockquote><br><br>I agree there are verses like this, where the Bible is poetic or uses analogy to make a point. One verse I can think of is Isaiah 52:10 - The LORD hath made bare his holy arm in the eyes of all the nations. It creates quite a mental picture of God rolling up His sleeves and showing His power. <br><br>But would it be inaccurate to also assume from this verse that God actually can have arms, like a man? Taken with other verses, such as &quot;let us make man in our image&quot; and how in Genesis 18, the Lord appeared to Abraham in the form of a man, that would seem a fair conclusion.<br><br>Taking a verse literally like Psalm 91:4 - He shall cover thee with his feathers, and under his wings shalt thou trust - along with about 10 other verses in psalms, as well as Ruth 2:12, might lead one to believe God has feathers on His arms or wings instead of arms. Maybe He does or maybe not; whether we take it as stated or poetically, it really doesn't alter the intended truth in the verse, that He will protect us.<br><br>I am really not questioning that there are literal or figurative aspects of the Bible. But the judgments we make about which are which can change the truth of the verse.</span>
