        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: Ned</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 9, 2009<br><br><blockquote>You wrote, “Jesus makes God personal.”  Yes, that’s quite true.  However God is quite Person, Personal, whether God ever became a human or not.  But, yes, God wanted very much to be Personal in ways we could understand, hear, feel, and touch.  You are right.  Jesus makes God <i>very</i> personal.<br>I am interested in your responses regarding these things.<br>Thanks for sharing.<br>John   (JohnJFarren)</blockquote><br><br>Well, I would say that God as the Father is a Person, that his creation has inherent meaning. As a part of his creation and made in his image, He couldn't be more personal to us. <br><br>What I was really commenting on here is the unique relationship that the Son establishes between humanity and God in comparison to other belief systems. <br><br>The God Vishnu took the incarnation of Krishna, but as this incarnation, he had a Mary Poppins version of Godhead. Krishna didn't weep. They didn't hang Krishna up on a cross. These aspects of Jesus make him very real... mainly that he suffered and died like all of us do. He knew ridicule and judgment. He knew loss. He also knew redemption, rejuvenation. This makes the whole drama of living meaningful. <br><br>Thanks for your comments John.</span>
