        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 9, 2009<br><br><blockquote>Even without Christ, God is not an enigma.  We know about God in two ways, by reason and by Revelation.  Reason itself is able to establish with certainty the existence of God and God’s principal attributes.  Many people cannot do that.  Many people can.  I <i>know</i> it can be done simply because many years ago <i>I did</i> it .. and it’s been a part of me ever since.</blockquote><br><br>Well, I would point out that there was no time in creation where we were without Christ, being that he is co-eternal with the Father and the Holy Spirit. But I understand what you mean. <br><br>To comment on what you are saying, we know God as the Logos or Word or Truth and that Truth is Being itself. Since we are made in God's image, we use our <i>logos</i> to comprehend and commune with <i>the</i> Logos.<br><br><blockquote>Regarding God there are many things we do not know.  In these things we “are surrounded by doubt,” or at least we’re in the dark.  There are also many things we DO know about God .. and many of these things are accurate -- incomplete, out of focus, perhaps, little appreciated .. but nevertheless true.</blockquote><br><br>Without establishing faith first, it is impossible to know God. I think this is where a lot of people go wrong (including me). We say, &quot;I want to know you before I believe in you.&quot;     <br><br>I was meditating on the idea of &quot;begotten, not made&quot; earlier. The obvious meaning is that Jesus was born of the Virgin Mary and not 'made' like the rest of us. On a deeper level, though, we keep trying to figure out the causality of Christ; how Christ is made. &quot;What are the steps? Give me a linear process to follow, so I can analyze the probable results.&quot; <br><br>It's not like that. &quot;Begotten&quot; is a direct, non-linear, non-causal relationship of the Father to the Son. And to know Christ means a sudden turn, a transformation of heart and mind, not an assembly line of salvation.</span>
