        June 8, 2009<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by Rev. Brandon A. Olivares</div><br><br>Jesus could display emotion because he also has a human nature. Not to mention he was within time when he was on earth.</blockquote><br><br>I'm still thinking about this, whether it would be possible for God to experience empathy and compassion, sadness or anger, as Jesus did. Those emotions are certainly not sinful because Jesus was without sin and in all ways, pleased God. I see Jesus as a manifestation of God on earth so I believe He was operating in a godly way, even in His emotional responses. <br><br>I agree God is not bound by time but I guess I think He is not excluded from experiencing it either. Jesus became human and limited himself to a body for a time.  I see no reason God, the Father or God, the Holy Spirit could not experience time and emotions while not being bound by a body.....unless all that is done through Jesus. But then wouldn't it be possible that God would or could be experiencing emotions because the three are all one?<br><br>I guess it's a different discussion from whether God experiences emotions to whether God is moved or motivated by emotions and I guess I would agree that He is not. So it may not matter whether He can feel them or not.   <br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by Rev. Brandon A. Olivares</div><br><br> I'm interested what others think, though</blockquote><br><br>Yea, me too. Any discussion that gets me cracking the Bible looking for the answers is good for me. Thanks for your thoughts.</span>
