        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: NightSpirit</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 8, 2009<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by Rev. Brandon A. Olivares</div><br><br>OK, here's what I've come to.<br><br>We know that God is immutable. If anyone disagrees I can post some verses, but I think it is pretty well-known..<br><br>God has a nature. That nature includes love, mercy, justice, and so forth. This nature does not change. God is never not loving, not merciful, or not just (apologies for the double negatives).</blockquote><br><br>No need for verses for me. I agree that God does not and has not changed and that God IS love and that whatever He does is merciful and just.<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by Rev. Brandon A. Olivares</div><br><br>God, however, cannot have emotion because that would require him to be in a temporary state. God is outside of time, so he cannot change.</blockquote><br><br>That temporary state part and how it relates to emotions is what I still am mulling over in my mind. <br><br>I have always experienced God's love as unconditional, and believe that there is nothing we can do that will cause Him to love us less or nothing we need to do to earn His love. Having faith in that love really does set us free from fear, as in 1 John 4:18, &quot;perfect love cast out all fear.&quot; So I'm not afraid God will get angry with me. Maybe correct me or chastise me, even punish me, but never turn against me.<br><br>As an aside, knowing God is love is why I have never had a problem with the idea of hell. I don't think any of us really can know for sure what it is actually going to be like on the other side. But because God has been so merciful and loving to me, I trust He is and will be the same for everyone. Whatever place of punishment or justice that exists, I trust in God's wisdom and mercy that it is necessary.<br><br>Looking back at some of the events of the old testament that appeared harsh, I have been able to be more open to the deeper spiritual truths being conveyed, if I remember that God always operates from His good nature, just as you described Him.<br><br>I was talking to a friend about this. He said he also believes that God doesn't get angry, that when we read about the earth opening up and swallowing some people, it's not because God lost control or went psychotic. We agreed that God operates, in punishment, from a fairness or composure similar to what  we expect from our law enforcement officers and courts, to be able to maintain order, and execute force if needed, without resorting to emotions.</span>
