        June 8, 2009<br><br>JMJ / MMM     090608<br>A Blessing on You, NightSpirit .. and Everybody --<br>What’s about “not literal”?  Examples= Oh, don’t beat around the bush!  There ain’t no bush.  And I’m not beating anything.  //  I’m gonna knock your block off!  You’d be arrested for nurder .. better not do it.  //  Said about somebody’s boss &gt; Boy! that guys a bear!  In actual fact, he’s not.  //  And .. she can wrap him around her little finger.  But you see the point.  In each of these statements there is meaning -- clearly understood.  You grasp the truth of them.  But taking each word at its face value .. they’re gibberish.<br><br>However, they are powerful and special ways of saying something.  The word “anthro” refers to man, to human beings.  There are times when Scripture speaks of God in terms of man, as if God were a human.being.  (We are not considering Jesus, True God and a true man, here.)  This is not a way of descendingly talking to dumb, little children.  It’s a manner of human speaking (under the inspiration of God) that is meant to add effect.<br><br>There is a time for “talking down” to people.  How should God have described the creation and formation of the world to the ancient Jews?  By explaining the Big Bang?  By explaining the relationship of matter to energy?  Or by using the words (which didn’t exist then and nor did their concepts) “prior” and “subsequent”?  No.  It was necessary to tell a story -- or not be understood at all -- of a man and a woman in a Garden with special trees and with a serpent who would talk and introduce a temptation.  It took many, many ages for that story to be properly understood.  For very many people, is that story understood today?  In its important, essential elements, yes.  But many people -- the security of their faith depends upon it -- take the story literally, word true for word true.  Well, that’s another story.<br><br>The key to the answer of the original question about God suffering essentially depends on the absolutely necessary truth that suffering involves change .. and on a (partial) understanding of the Incarnation.<br>Blessing to all!         John   (JohnJFarren)</span>
