        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 8, 2009<br><br>JMJ / MMM     090608<br>Greetings, Ned .. and Everybody --<br>Because the Trinity is a mystery of our faith, that doesn’t mean we can know nothing about it.  There is a good bit we can and do know.<br>To separate the Christ from Jesus .. as you say you do .. is a mistaken approach.  Let us suppose &gt; I come upon you unexpectedly and I give your right hand a mighty whack!  You react instantaneously with, “Why did you <i>hit</i> me!”  <font size="1">(You might have reacted with, “Why did you hit my hand!”  But I doubt it.)</font>  Let’s stick with, “Why did you hit me!”  If I said that I didn’t hit <i>you</i>, I hit your <i>hand</i> .. my separating you from your hand would puzzle you a little.  As far as you’re concerned I did hit <i>you</i>.<br>In Jesus Christ there are not two persons.  There are two natures, the Divine Nature and a human nature, both possessed by the same One Person, the Second of the Trinity.  The human nature of Christ is possessed by, belongs to, the Second Divine Person in the same way your human nature is possessed by, belongs to, <i>you</i>, the one <i>person you</i>.<br>When one grasps strongly what this means, it truly takes an act of faith to believe it!<br>Even without Christ, God is not an enigma.  We know about God in two ways, by reason and by Revelation.  Reason itself is able to establish with certainty the existence of God and God’s principal attributes.  Many people cannot do that.  Many people can.  I <i>know</i> it can be done simply because many years ago <i>I did</i> it .. and it’s been a part of me ever since.<br>Regarding God there are many things we do not know.  In these things we “are surrounded by doubt,” or at least we’re in the dark.  There are also many things we DO know about God .. and many of these things are accurate -- incomplete, out of focus, perhaps, little appreciated .. but nevertheless true.<br>You wrote, “Jesus makes God personal.”  Yes, that’s quite true.  However God is quite Person, Personal, whether God ever became a human or not.  But, yes, God wanted very much to be Personal in ways we could understand, hear, feel, and touch.  You are right.  Jesus makes God <i>very</i> personal.<br>I am interested in your responses regarding these things.<br>Thanks for sharing.<br>John   (JohnJFarren)   <a href="mailto:Trinity5635@aol.com">Trinity5635@aol.com</a></span>
