        June 7, 2009<br><br>JMJ / MMM     090607<br>Hi Brandon --<br>The backup you seek would not best be found in CCC but rather in more detailed and specific theological dogma manuals.  In writings I know of by Fr William Most -- a distinguished and very clear theologian -- I believe I can offer you much more satisfying info. I will search for that and share with you here on the forum a website.<br><br>Yes, many times in the Bible God is spoken of as having emotions/feelings such as we have. All of these times are an anthropomorphically manner of speaking .. and are not literal. These ways of speaking are sometimes necessary and beneficial for us human and emotional/feeling/passionate creatures. God Himself obviously used them in the inspiration He worked in the writers of Scripture.<br><br>I'll be back with some &quot;Trinity&quot; info that can help.<br>John   (JohnJFarren)</span>
